<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-971-744  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 971 744.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  Nov 1989 p15(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Design for assembly.(Includes related articles on design forassembly.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Withers, Lucia.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Simplifying a product's design and reducing its number of partscan make its assembly easier, and is an excellent way to increasemanufacturing productivity.andP;  Design-for-assembly (DSA) softwarehas been developed to help achieve this by focusing on themanufacturing process as a product is designed.andP;  Such packagescapture product structure, estimate assembly times and costs ofcomponents, establish efficiency ratings, identify opportunitiesfor product structure simplification, and design for ease ofassembly.andP;  In addition to providing savings on assembly times andcosts, DFA methods and software can simplify all aspects of auser's business, and can result in manual assembly methods thatare just as efficient and economical as highly automatedtechniques.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     DesignManufacturingSoftwareEconomics of Computing.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>